<h1>📦 Part 2: Product Related Masters</h1>
<p>Manages products, lines, and distribution divisions.</p>
<h2>2.1 Division Master</h3>
<p>The Division Master manages division information. It uses a structured alphanumeric code system (e.g. <code>DI0001</code>, <code>DI0002</code>).</p>

<table style="width:100%">
    <tr>
        <th>Table Name</th>
        <th>Columns & Constraints</th>
        <th>Core Rules</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><code>Tbl_Div_Mst</code></td>
        <td>
            <code>c_code</code> VARCHAR(10) Primary Key<br />
            <code>c_name</code> VARCHAR(50) Not Null (Unique Name)<br />
            <code>c_sh_name</code> VARCHAR(7) Nullable<br />
            <code>n_deleted</code> SMALLINT Default 0 (Active)<br />
            <code>d_created</code> TIMESTAMP, <code>d_modified</code> TIMESTAMP<br />
            <code>c_modifier</code> VARCHAR(10)
        </td>
        <td>
            * Unique case-insensitive names<br />
            * Alphanumeric pattern <code>DI[0-9]+</code><br />
            * Soft delete via <code>n_deleted = 1</code>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

---

<h3>2.1.1 Get Next Division Code</h3>
<p><span class="badge badge-get">GET</span> <code>/api/masters/division/next-code</code></p>
<p><strong>Description:</strong> Auto-calculates the next division code in the sequence (e.g. if the highest code is <code>DI0001</code>, it suggests <code>DI0002</code>).</p>

<h3>Database Queries Executed:</h3>
<pre>SELECT "c_code" 
FROM "Tbl_Div_Mst"
WHERE "c_code" ~ '^DI[0-9]+$'
ORDER BY CAST(SUBSTRING("c_code" FROM 3) AS INTEGER) DESC
LIMIT 1;</pre>

<div class="explanation-box">
    <div class="explanation-title">💡 Human Explanation of the Query:</div>
    This query calculates the next numeric code in the database.
    <ol>
        <li>We use PostgreSQL's regular expression match operator (<code>~</code>) with the pattern <code>'^DI[0-9]+$'</code> to filter for codes that start with "DI" and end with numbers, ignoring any manual anomalies.</li>
        <li>We use <code>SUBSTRING("c_code" FROM 3)</code> to strip the "DI" prefix, leaving only the digits (e.g., "DI0001" becomes "0001").</li>
        <li>We use <code>CAST(... AS INTEGER)</code> to convert the numeric string into an integer. Without this cast, sorting lexicographically would order "DI9" as greater than "DI10".</li>
        <li>We sort the integers in descending order (<code>DESC</code>) and retrieve the top result (<code>LIMIT 1</code>) to find the highest number in the system. The application then increments this integer by 1 and pads it to four digits. If the table is empty, the system defaults to <code>DI0001</code>.</li>
    </ol>
</div>

---

<h3>2.1.2 Create Division</h3>
<p><span class="badge badge-post">POST</span> <code>/api/masters/division</code></p>
<p><strong>Description:</strong> Creates a new division. It enforces case-insensitive name uniqueness among active divisions.</p>

<h3>Database Queries Executed:</h3>

<h4>Query 1: Case-Insensitive Duplicate Check</h4>
<pre>SELECT "c_code" 
FROM "Tbl_Div_Mst"
WHERE LOWER("c_name") = LOWER($1) -- $1: New division name proposed by user
  AND "n_deleted" = 0;</pre>

<div class="explanation-box">
    <div class="explanation-title">💡 Human Explanation of the Query:</div>
    This query checks for name duplicates. 
    By applying the <code>LOWER()</code> function to both the database column and the user input, we run a case-insensitive check. This prevents duplicate entries like "Pharma" and "pharma". 
    We also append <code>AND "n_deleted" = 0</code> to ignore divisions that have been soft-deleted.
</div>

<h4>Query 2: Insert Division</h4>
<pre>INSERT INTO "Tbl_Div_Mst" (
  "c_code", 
  "c_name", 
  "c_sh_name", 
  "n_deleted", 
  "d_created", 
  "c_modifier"
)
VALUES (
  $1, -- $1: Sequential generated code (e.g. 'DI0002')
  $2, -- $2: Trimmed division name (e.g. 'Pharma')
  $3, -- $3: Trimmed short name (e.g. 'PH', optional)
  0,  -- 0: active status (not deleted)
  NOW(), -- Current database timestamp
  $4  -- $4: User ID of creating administrator
);</pre>

<div class="explanation-box">
    <div class="explanation-title">💡 Human Explanation of the Query:</div>
    Once the code is generated and duplication checks pass, we insert the record. 
    The division is initialized as active (<code>n_deleted = 0</code>), stamped with the current time (<code>NOW()</code>), and associated with the admin who created it (<code>c_modifier</code>).
</div>

---

<h3>2.1.3 Get All / Search Divisions</h3>
<p><span class="badge badge-get">GET</span> <code>/api/masters/division</code></p>
<p><strong>Description:</strong> Retrieves a paginated, searchable list of divisions. It supports wildcard searches (`*` is translated to database `%`).</p>

<h3>Database Queries Executed:</h3>
<pre>SELECT 
  "c_code", 
  "c_name", 
  "c_sh_name", 
  "d_created", 
  "d_modified", 
  COUNT(*) OVER() AS total_count -- Virtual column calculating total records matching query filters
FROM "Tbl_Div_Mst"
WHERE "n_deleted" = 0
  AND LOWER("c_name") LIKE LOWER($1) -- $1: Wildcard pattern for name (e.g. '%sales%')
  AND LOWER("c_code") LIKE LOWER($2) -- $2: Wildcard pattern for code (e.g. 'DI%')
ORDER BY "c_code"
LIMIT $3    -- $3: Paging limits size (e.g. 10)
OFFSET $4;</pre>

<div class="explanation-box">
    <div class="explanation-title">💡 Human Explanation of the Query:</div>
    This query retrieves data for list views.
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Partial Wildcard Search:</strong> We use the <code>LIKE</code> operator alongside <code>LOWER()</code> to search divisions. If a user types <code>Pharm*</code>, the code converts the asterisk to <code>%</code> (rendering <code>pharm%</code>) to fetch all divisions starting with "Pharm".</li>
        <li><strong>Single-Query Pagination (Window Function):</strong> We append <code>COUNT(*) OVER() as total_count</code>. This window function calculates the total number of records matching the filters across the entire dataset and returns this count in a virtual column on every row. This avoids running a separate <code>SELECT COUNT(*)</code> query, saving a database round-trip.</li>
        <li><strong>Pagination Boundaries:</strong> <code>LIMIT</code> restricts the number of rows returned per page, and <code>OFFSET</code> skips rows from previous pages.</li>
    </ul>
</div>

---

<h3>2.1.4 Update Division</h3>
<p><span class="badge badge-put">PUT</span> <code>/api/masters/division/:code</code></p>
<p><strong>Description:</strong> Updates an existing division's name and short name. It verifies that the target exists and that the new name does not conflict with another division.</p>

<h3>Database Queries Executed:</h3>

<h4>Query 1: Verify Record Exists</h4>
<pre>SELECT "c_code" 
FROM "Tbl_Div_Mst" 
WHERE "c_code" = $1 -- $1: Route code param (e.g. 'DI0001')
  AND "n_deleted" = 0;</pre>

<div class="explanation-box">
    <div class="explanation-title">💡 Human Explanation of the Query:</div>
    Verifies that the division we are trying to edit exists and is active. If this check fails, the API returns a 404 Not Found error.
</div>

<h4>Query 2: Uniqueness Check (Excluding Self)</h4>
<pre>SELECT "c_code" 
FROM "Tbl_Div_Mst" 
WHERE LOWER("c_name") = LOWER($1) -- $1: New division name proposed
  AND "n_deleted" = 0 
  AND "c_code" != $2;             -- $2: Exclude the record currently being modified</pre>

<div class="explanation-box">
    <div class="explanation-title">💡 Human Explanation of the Query:</div>
    When renaming a division, we check if the new name is already taken by another record. We append <code>AND "c_code" != $2</code> to exclude the current record from the check, allowing the user to update other fields (like the short name) without triggering a duplicate error.
</div>

<h4>Query 3: Apply Updates</h4>
<pre>UPDATE "Tbl_Div_Mst"
SET 
  "c_name" = $1,      -- $1: New division name
  "c_sh_name" = $2,   -- $2: New short name
  "d_modified" = NOW(), 
  "c_modifier" = $3   -- $3: User ID of modifying administrator
WHERE "c_code" = $4;  -- $4: Target code to modify (e.g. 'DI0001')</pre>

<div class="explanation-box">
    <div class="explanation-title">💡 Human Explanation of the Query:</div>
    Applies the changes, updates the modification timestamp (<code>d_modified</code>), and logs the admin user ID (<code>c_modifier</code>).
</div>

---

<h3>2.1.5 Delete Division (Soft Delete)</h3>
<p><span class="badge badge-delete">DELETE</span> <code>/api/masters/division/:code</code></p>
<p><strong>Description:</strong> Soft-deletes a division, removing it from active lists while preserving historical data integrity.</p>

<h3>Database Queries Executed:</h3>
<pre>UPDATE "Tbl_Div_Mst"
SET 
  "n_deleted" = 1, 
  "d_modified" = NOW(), 
  "c_modifier" = $1 -- $1: User ID of admin deleting the record
WHERE "c_code" = $2;  -- $2: Target code to soft delete (e.g. 'DI0001')</pre>

<div class="explanation-box">
    <div class="explanation-title">💡 Human Explanation of the Query:</div>
    Rather than using a destructive <code>DELETE FROM</code> query, we perform a soft delete by setting <code>n_deleted = 1</code>. 
    This hides the division from active lookup lists while retaining the record for referential integrity (e.g., in case historical sales link to this division code). We also log the modification time and the admin who performed the deletion.
</div>


